title="Forester 4.0">Forester 4.0</fr:link> › enhanced XML support</fr:link> › emitting XML and resolving namespaces</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>4</fr:month><fr:day>5</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00RH</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Since <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00CW.xml"
addr="jms-00CW"
title="Forester 3.0">version 3.0</fr:link>, <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00CZ.xml"
addr="jms-00CZ"
title="Forester 3.0 › breaking changes › fall-through of undefined identifiers">Forester’s source language has supported</fr:link> a limited form of custom XML output by means of the <fr:code><![CDATA[\xml]]></fr:code> command. This support was, however, somewhat unwieldy: no built-in accounting for XML namespaces was included, so correct  usage of <fr:code><![CDATA[\xml]]></fr:code> was prohibitively difficult because of the need for <fr:code>xmlns</fr:code> attributes on essentially every node.</fr:p><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>753</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">jms-00RK</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00RK.xml</fr:route><fr:title
text="XML namespace declaration">XML namespace declaration</fr:title><fr:taxon>Feature</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>4</fr:month><fr:day>5</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00RJ</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p><fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-005P.xml"
addr="jms-005P"
title="Forester">Forester</fr:link> treats XML namespace prefixes in a way that respects <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha ]]></fr:tex>-equivalence: in other words, any prefix mentioned must be <fr:em>bound</fr:em>, and it is possible for two different textually identical namespace prefixes to denote different namespaces depending on their scope. This makes it possible to compose code that emits XML without coordinating namespace prefixes, which I have found to be a major impediment to the correct use of XML for non-trivial work.</fr:p><fr:p>An XML namespace prefix is bound by a declaration like the following:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\xmlns:html{http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml}]]></fr:pre><fr:p>This declaration has the same scoping rules as <fr:code><![CDATA[\def]]></fr:code>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
toc="true"
